74#define OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX 8
75OPENSSL_STATIC_ASSERT(OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX >= sizeof(size_t),
76 "size_t too large");
77
78#if defined(OPENSSL_ASAN)
79void __asan_poison_memory_region(const volatile void *addr, size_t size);
80void __asan_unpoison_memory_region(const volatile void *addr, size_t size);
81#else
82static void __asan_poison_memory_region(const void *addr, size_t size) {}
83static void __asan_unpoison_memory_region(const void *addr, size_t size) {}
84#endif

86// Windows doesn't really support weak symbols as of May 2019, and Clang on
87// Windows will emit strong symbols instead. See
88// https://bugs.llvm.org/show_bug.cgi?id=37598
89#if defined(__ELF__) && defined(__GNUC__)
90#define WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(rettype, name, args) \
91 rettype name args __attribute__((weak));
92#else
93#define WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(rettype, name, args) static rettype(*name) args = NULL;
94#endif
95
96// sdallocx is a sized |free| function. By passing the size (which we happen to
97// always know in BoringSSL), the malloc implementation can save work. We cannot
98// depend on |sdallocx| being available, however, so it's a weak symbol.
99//
100// This will always be safe, but will only be overridden if the malloc
101// implementation is statically linked with BoringSSL. So, if |sdallocx| is
102// provided in, say, libc.so, we still won't use it because that's dynamically
103// linked. This isn't an ideal result, but its helps in some cases.
104WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(void, sdallocx, (void *ptr, size_t size, int flags));
105
106// The following three functions can be defined to override default heap
107// allocation and freeing. If defined, it is the responsibility of
108// |OPENSSL_memory_free| to zero out the memory before returning it to the
109// system. |OPENSSL_memory_free| will not be passed NULL pointers.
110//
111// WARNING: These functions are called on every allocation and free in
112// BoringSSL across the entire process. They may be called by any code in the
113// process which calls BoringSSL, including in process initializers and thread
114// destructors. When called, BoringSSL may hold pthreads locks. Any other code
115// in the process which, directly or indirectly, calls BoringSSL may be on the
116// call stack and may itself be using arbitrary synchronization primitives.
117//
118// As a result, these functions may not have the usual programming environment
119// available to most C or C++ code. In particular, they may not call into
120// BoringSSL, or any library which depends on BoringSSL. Any synchronization
121// primitives used must tolerate every other synchronization primitive linked
122// into the process, including pthreads locks. Failing to meet these constraints
123// may result in deadlocks, crashes, or memory corruption.
124WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(void*, OPENSSL_memory_alloc, (size_t size));
125WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(void, OPENSSL_memory_free, (void *ptr));
126WEAK_SYMBOL_FUNC(size_t, OPENSSL_memory_get_size, (void *ptr));
127
128void *OPENSSL_malloc(size_t size) {
129 if (OPENSSL_memory_alloc != NULL) {
130 assert(OPENSSL_memory_free != NULL);
131 assert(OPENSSL_memory_get_size != NULL);
132 return OPENSSL_memory_alloc(size);
133 }
134
135 if (size + OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX < size) {
136 return NULL;
137 }
138
139 void *ptr = malloc(size + OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
140 if (ptr == NULL) {
141 return NULL;
142 }
143
144 *(size_t *)ptr = size;
145
146 __asan_poison_memory_region(ptr, OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
147 return ((uint8_t *)ptr) + OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX;
148}
149
150void OPENSSL_free(void *orig_ptr) {
151 if (orig_ptr == NULL) {
152 return;
153 }
154
155 if (OPENSSL_memory_free != NULL) {
156 OPENSSL_memory_free(orig_ptr);
157 return;
158 }
159
160 void *ptr = ((uint8_t *)orig_ptr) - OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX;
161 __asan_unpoison_memory_region(ptr, OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
162
163 size_t size = *(size_t *)ptr;
164 OPENSSL_cleanse(ptr, size + OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
165 if (sdallocx) {
166 sdallocx(ptr, size + OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX, 0 /* flags */);
167 } else {
168 free(ptr);
169 }
170}
171
172void *OPENSSL_realloc(void *orig_ptr, size_t new_size) {
173 if (orig_ptr == NULL) {
174 return OPENSSL_malloc(new_size);
175 }
176
177 size_t old_size;
178 if (OPENSSL_memory_get_size != NULL) {
179 old_size = OPENSSL_memory_get_size(orig_ptr);
180 } else {
181 void *ptr = ((uint8_t *)orig_ptr) - OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX;
182 __asan_unpoison_memory_region(ptr, OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
183 old_size = *(size_t *)ptr;
184 __asan_poison_memory_region(ptr, OPENSSL_MALLOC_PREFIX);
185 }
186
187 void *ret = OPENSSL_malloc(new_size);
188 if (ret == NULL) {
189 return NULL;
190 }
191
192 size_t to_copy = new_size;
193 if (old_size < to_copy) {
194 to_copy = old_size;
195 }
196
197 memcpy(ret, orig_ptr, to_copy);
198 OPENSSL_free(orig_ptr);
199
200 return ret;
201}
202
203void OPENSSL_cleanse(void *ptr, size_t len) {
204#if defined(OPENSSL_WINDOWS)
205 SecureZeroMemory(ptr, len);
206#else
207 OPENSSL_memset(ptr, 0, len);
208
209#if !defined(OPENSSL_NO_ASM)
210 /* As best as we can tell, this is sufficient to break any optimisations that
211 might try to eliminate "superfluous" memsets. If there's an easy way to
212 detect memset_s, it would be better to use that. */
213 __asm__ __volatile__("" : : "r"(ptr) : "memory");
214#endif
215#endif // !OPENSSL_NO_ASM
216}
217
218void OPENSSL_clear_free(void *ptr, size_t unused) {
219 OPENSSL_free(ptr);
220}

222int CRYPTO_memcmp(const void *in_a, const void *in_b, size_t len) {
223 const uint8_t *a = in_a;
224 const uint8_t *b = in_b;
225 uint8_t x = 0;
226
227 for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
228 x |= a[i] ^ b[i];
229 }
230
231 return x;
232}
233
234uint32_t OPENSSL_hash32(const void *ptr, size_t len) {
235 // These are the FNV-1a parameters for 32 bits.
236 static const uint32_t kPrime = 16777619u;
237 static const uint32_t kOffsetBasis = 2166136261u;
238
239 const uint8_t *in = ptr;
240 uint32_t h = kOffsetBasis;
241
242 for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
243 h ^= in[i];
244 h *= kPrime;
245 }
246
247 return h;
248}
249
250size_t OPENSSL_strnlen(const char *s, size_t len) {
251 for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
252 if (s[i] == 0) {
253 return i;
254 }
255 }
256
257 return len;
258}
259
260char *OPENSSL_strdup(const char *s) {
261 if (s == NULL) {
262 return NULL;
263 }
264 const size_t len = strlen(s) + 1;
265 char *ret = OPENSSL_malloc(len);
266 if (ret == NULL) {
267 return NULL;
268 }
269 OPENSSL_memcpy(ret, s, len);
270 return ret;
271}
272
273int OPENSSL_tolower(int c) {
274 if (c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z') {
275 return c + ('a' - 'A');
276 }
277 return c;
278}
279
280int OPENSSL_strcasecmp(const char *a, const char *b) {
281 for (size_t i = 0;; i++) {
282 const int aa = OPENSSL_tolower(a[i]);
283 const int bb = OPENSSL_tolower(b[i]);
284
285 if (aa < bb) {
286 return -1;
287 } else if (aa > bb) {
288 return 1;
289 } else if (aa == 0) {
290 return 0;
291 }
292 }
293}
294
295int OPENSSL_strncasecmp(const char *a, const char *b, size_t n) {
296 for (size_t i = 0; i < n; i++) {
297 const int aa = OPENSSL_tolower(a[i]);
298 const int bb = OPENSSL_tolower(b[i]);
299
300 if (aa < bb) {
301 return -1;
302 } else if (aa > bb) {
303 return 1;
304 } else if (aa == 0) {
305 return 0;
306 }
307 }
308
309 return 0;
310}

312int BIO_snprintf(char *buf, size_t n, const char *format, ...) {
313 va_list args;
314 va_start(args, format);
315 int ret = BIO_vsnprintf(buf, n, format, args);
316 va_end(args);
317 return ret;
318}
319
320int BIO_vsnprintf(char *buf, size_t n, const char *format, va_list args) {
321 return vsnprintf(buf, n, format, args);
322}

324char *OPENSSL_strndup(const char *str, size_t size) {
325 char *ret;
326 size_t alloc_size;
327
328 if (str == NULL) {
329 return NULL;
330 }
331
332 size = OPENSSL_strnlen(str, size);
333
334 alloc_size = size + 1;
335 if (alloc_size < size) {
336 // overflow
337 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(CRYPTO, ERR_R_MALLOC_FAILURE);
338 return NULL;
339 }
340 ret = OPENSSL_malloc(alloc_size);
341 if (ret == NULL) {
342 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(CRYPTO, ERR_R_MALLOC_FAILURE);
343 return NULL;
344 }
345
346 OPENSSL_memcpy(ret, str, size);
347 ret[size] = '\0';
348 return ret;
349}
350
351size_t OPENSSL_strlcpy(char *dst, const char *src, size_t dst_size) {
352 size_t l = 0;
353
354 for (; dst_size > 1 && *src; dst_size--) {
355 *dst++ = *src++;
356 l++;
357 }
358
359 if (dst_size) {
360 *dst = 0;
361 }
362
363 return l + strlen(src);
364}
365
366size_t OPENSSL_strlcat(char *dst, const char *src, size_t dst_size) {
367 size_t l = 0;
368 for (; dst_size > 0 && *dst; dst_size--, dst++) {
369 l++;
370 }
371 return l + OPENSSL_strlcpy(dst, src, dst_size);
372}
373
374void *OPENSSL_memdup(const void *data, size_t size) {
375 if (size == 0) {
376 return NULL;
377 }
378
379 void *ret = OPENSSL_malloc(size);
380 if (ret == NULL) {
381 OPENSSL_PUT_ERROR(CRYPTO, ERR_R_MALLOC_FAILURE);
382 return NULL;
383 }
384
385 OPENSSL_memcpy(ret, data, size);
386 return ret;
387}
